I don't think the comparison is necessarily bad. The people that want to play the "best" are going to do so, and those that want to build for fun will do that. Really not a huge deal.

The comparison isn’t bad in a vacuum, but to quote <@U3L7A68JC> “people are the worst.”

I’m on Reddit and other forums enough to see and hear enough people trash commanders over smaller comparisons.
I just get annoyed over the “why would I ever play this garbage?” comments that I see.

Those do get to me every once in a while... but then I remember that I know the people like that in real life, and they're the same ones constantly asking why no one wants to play with them (despite everyone telling them exactly why).

I write about commanders with more powerful alternatives all the time. Even if I personally think one has supplanted the other, that's not useful, which is why I never say it. What can Storrev and Jarad do that Meren can't? Lean into that and you become a better deckbuilder.
to address <@U286Q175Y>'s question, compare popularity history timelines between commanders in the same theme group
could peg timeslices to set releases
keep an avg decks/week count per commander. watch for when they dip, then when they do, compare to other commanders in the same themes and color slices
new commanders that gain counts might be the new royalty if the trend lasts. old commanders that gain counts might be boosted by cards in the new set
then at that point old commanders that lose counts can get tagged with an associated "why they lost" card
new commanders that never gained enough counts get tagged with "meren is better" card
and thus each commander has their own popularity kryptonite
unless they are meren
etc
